07262nam a22008655i 9780824840198DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248401987 a10.1515/97808248401982doi  a(DE-B1597)484004  a(OCoLC)1024049450  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0020102bisacsh00aGender on the Edge :bTransgender, Gay, and Other Pacific Islanders /ced. by Niko Besnier, Kalissa Alexeyeff. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b14 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1: Gender on the Edge Identities, Politics, Transformations -- tPart I: Historical Transformations -- tChapter 2: Queer History and Its Discontents at Tahiti The Contested Politics of Modernity and Sexual Subjectivity -- tChapter 3: “Hollywood” and the Emergence of a Fa‘afafine Social Movement in Samoa, 1960–1980 -- tChapter 4: Representing Fa‘afafine Sex, Socialization, and Gender Identity in Samoa -- tPart II: Performing Gender -- tChapter 5: Living as and Living with Māhū and Raerae Geopolitics, Sex, and Gender in the Society Islands -- tChapter 6: Transgender in Samoa The Cultural Production of Gender Inequality -- tChapter 7: Re-Visioning Family Māhūwahine and Male-to-Female Transgender in Contemporary Hawai‘i -- tChapter 8: Men Trapped in Women’s Clothing Homosexuality, Cross-Dressing, and Masculinity in Fiji -- tChapter 9: Two Sea Turtles Intimacy between Men in the Marshall Islands -- tPart III: Politics of the Global -- tChapter 10: The Fokisi and the Fakaleitī Provocative Performances in Tonga -- tChapter 11: Televisual Transgender Hybridizing the Mainstream in Pasifika New Zealand -- tChapter 12: Same Sex, Different Armies Sexual Minority Invisibility among Fijians in the Fiji Military Forces and British Army -- tChapter 13: In Sickness and in Health Evolving Trends in Gay Rights Advocacy in Fiji -- tChapter 14: On the Edge of Understanding Non-Heteronormative Sexuality in Papua New Guinea -- tChapter 15: Outwith the Law in Samoa and Tonga -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTransgender identities and other forms of gender and sexuality that transcend the normative pose important questions about society, culture, politics, and history. They force us to question, for example, the forces that divide humanity into two gender categories and render them necessary, inevitable, and natural. The transgender also exposes a host of dynamics that, at first glance, have little to do with gender or sex, such as processes of power and domination; the complex relationship among agency, subjectivity, and structure; and the mutual constitution of the global and the local.Particularly intriguing is the fact that gender and sexual diversity appear to be more prevalent in some regions of the world than in others. This edited volume is an exploration of the ways in which non-normative gendering and sexuality in one such region, the Pacific Islands, are implicated in a wide range of socio-cultural dynamics that are at once local and global, historical, and contemporary. The authors recognize that different social configurations, cultural contexts, and historical trajectories generate diverse ways of being transgender across the societies of the region, but they also acknowledge that these differences are overlaid with commonalities and predictabilities. Rather than focus on the definition of identities, they engage with the fact that identities do things, that they are performed in everyday life, that they are transformed through events and movements, and that they are constantly negotiated. By addressing the complexities of these questions over time and space, this work provides a model for future endeavors that seek to embed dynamics of gender and sexuality in a broad field of theoretical import.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGayszOceania. 0aSex rolezOceania. 0aTransgender peoplezOceania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAlexeyeff, Kalissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexeyeff, Kalissa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBesnier, Niko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesnier, Niko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDolgoy, Reevan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDvorak, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliston, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarran, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Mary K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkeda, Linda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuwahara, Makiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Sarina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPresterudstuen, Geir Henning, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTcherkézoff, Serge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTeaiwa, Teresia K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484019840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/i